      "pronunciation": "ˈɡɔɫˌbɫædɝ",
      "senses": [
        {
          "definition": "a small, pear-shaped organ located beneath the liver in which the body stores a strong digestive fluid produced by the liver",
          "examples": [
            {
              "cf": "",
              "x": "The gallbladder plays a crucial role in the digestive process by storing bile produced by the liver until it's needed for digestion."
            },
            {
              "cf": "",
              "x": "When fatty foods are consumed, the gallbladder contracts and releases bile into the small intestine to help emulsify fats and aid in their digestion."
            },
            {
              "cf": "",
              "x": "Gallstones, hardened deposits that can form in the gallbladder, may cause discomfort, pain, and other complications, sometimes requiring medical intervention."
            },
            {
              "cf": "",
              "x": "In cases of severe gallbladder disease or gallstones, surgical removal of the gallbladder, known as cholecystectomy, may be necessary to alleviate symptoms and prevent complications."
            },
            {
              "cf": "",
              "x": "The absence of a gallbladder doesn't typically impair digestion significantly, as bile can still flow from the liver directly into the small intestine, albeit in a less concentrated manner."
            }
          ]
        }
